        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1277283520" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12811393282782663896">(From a Goodreads giveaway.)<br/><br/>I was turned off by this book&apos;s premise, which is that everyone&apos;s reason for working is to make as much money as possible. She points to the fact that we wouldn&apos;t do our work for free as proof of this premise. But just because I wouldn&apos;t do the work for free doesn&apos;t mean that money is or should be the ONLY consideration. I could make a lot more money selling my panties on the internet than I do at my current job, but that&apos;s not enough reason to switch. Or, a less extr</span>
  <span id="freeText12811393282782663896" style="display:none">(From a Goodreads giveaway.)<br /><br />I was turned off by this book's premise, which is that everyone's reason for working is to make as much money as possible. She points to the fact that we wouldn't do our work for free as proof of this premise. But just because I wouldn't do the work for free doesn't mean that money is or should be the ONLY consideration. I could make a lot more money selling my panties on the internet than I do at my current job, but that's not enough reason to switch. Or, a less extreme example: I could make more at a salary position, but it would mean too much time away from my kids and schoolwork. <br /><br />There are a lot of good principles in here, some of which should have been common sense, but were somewhat new to me (like managing up, and not bringing your personal issues to your boss). But I got tired of reading "the loyalty-free workplace" an average of once a page.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12811393282782663896" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


