<div id="review_1363633811" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1363633811" />
    <a title="Dannielle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24777142-dannielle"><img alt="Dannielle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1382031629p2/24777142.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1363633811?book_show_action=true">Aug 14, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dannielle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dannielle" href="/user/show/24777142-dannielle">Dannielle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1363633811" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8847433751794623947">The Perpetual Paycheck is a must read for job seekers. It bears a realistic but positive approach to finding a job, keeping a job, and finding a better job. Since there are few jobs that guarantee long-term security these days, the skills this book will give you are essential.<br/><br/>This book won&apos;t pull the wool over your eyes or fill you with fanciful ideas of following your passion or any other &quot;fluff.&quot; It cuts to the chase and perhaps can seem a little harsh to readers who have their head in the clo</span>
  <span id="freeText8847433751794623947" style="display:none">The Perpetual Paycheck is a must read for job seekers. It bears a realistic but positive approach to finding a job, keeping a job, and finding a better job. Since there are few jobs that guarantee long-term security these days, the skills this book will give you are essential.<br /><br />This book won't pull the wool over your eyes or fill you with fanciful ideas of following your passion or any other "fluff." It cuts to the chase and perhaps can seem a little harsh to readers who have their head in the clouds and were expecting a pep talk. This is not a bad thing though. To succeed in the job market, a person needs to destroy their illusions, whether they're self-imposed or from other sources that just tried to boost their ego. We need to wake up to the realities of modern business if we are to make a good living.<br /><br />I personally learned a lot from this book. It's full of practical advice, some of which are well-known to job seekers but explained better, some of which are completely new to me but get me thinking, "Aha! Why didn't I consider this before? It makes so much sense now." The author expertly explains the strategies she uses for herself as well as gives to her clients to help them achieve career success. Though this book doesn't blow any smoke or paint the market in a rosy glow, it actually does boost my confidence in seeking employment, because now I know some of the inside secrets of success that other materials I've read on the topic fail to address because they are too busy being overly optimistic. That approach doesn't work; it just sets you up for disappointment. This approach is much more useful in the long run. Knowing that you are not owed a thing in the job market and that employers are not obliged to take care of you empowers you to take control of your future and make your career into the success you want it to be.<br /><br />I highly recommend this to anyone who feels stuck in the job hunting experience when you seem to be using the right strategies and not getting the results you'd expect. This book can give you the little something extra to land a good job and keep your career moving forward. You won't be disappointed!</span>
  <a data-text-id="8847433751794623947" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

